  "prompt": "What are those lines called that are used instead of parenthesis?",
  "response": "The lines that are used instead of parentheses are typically called \"brackets\" or, more specifically, \"square brackets.\" They look like this: [ ]. In some contexts, you might also encounter \"curly braces\" or \"curly brackets,\" which look like this: { }. These symbols are often used in various fields such as mathematics, programming, and writing to indicate grouping, sets, or intervals, among other purposes.",
